{"actual_usd":0.160125,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":292,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31149,"reply":"\"I don't think the cross was God working himself up to mercy.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the bright square, where somebody's bucket chain gives one thin metallic clink.* \"I think it was mercy refusing to become cheap.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench a second, trying to say it plain.* \"Could God have just declared forgiveness? I mean, he's God. But then you get the question of whether evil actually matters, whether sin is a real wound or just something waved away. The cross says both things at once: God really does forgive, and what we're being forgiven for is terrible enough to cost blood.\"\n\n\"And more than that—\" *I lean forward a little.* \"—it isn't only a legal trick. It's God entering the full human wreckage instead of pardoning us from a safe height. If Christ just says, 'all clear,' without stepping into death, then he stays above the flood. In the cross, he comes all the way in.\"\n\n*I let out a small breath.* \"So... could he have done something else? Maybe in the abstract, I don't know. But this is the way that tells the truth about both his holiness and his love. It feels like the kind of answer God gives when he doesn't want forgiveness to be a slogan.\"\n\n\"What part of it catches in you—the justice piece, or the 'why blood at all' piece?\"","rolling_24h_usd":46.218990000000026,"run_id":"40a43251-a952-4176-bc08-a6b94d7d077b"}
